\section{Adapted letters}
 \label{sec:adapted-letters}


 \subsection{\textit{g improprie}}
 \label{sec:g-improprio}

 This is the letter \textit{g} as written by Italians (\textit{unco
   retorto versus dexteram partem sicut scribunt ipsum Italici}).

 The letter was transliterated as \ucode{A77F} \uname{LATIN SMALL
   LETTER TURNED INSULAR G} (\gl{ꝿ}, Latin Ex\-tended-D block).

 In Junicode the glyph is {\gl{g\&\_\_p;\&\_\_h;}} and the
 input is {\Ji{g\&\_\_p;\&\_\_h;}}.

 \subsection{\textit{grossum m}}
 \label{sec:grossum-m}

 This is the letter \textit{m} as written at the end of words
 (\textit{[\ldots]\ spissum cum cauda, sicut in fine diccionum poni
   solet}). As discussed in \cite[p.~48]{bień22:_parkos}, the intended
 shape of the letter is not clear.
 
 The letter was transliterated as \ucode{0271} \uname{LATIN SMALL
   LETTER M WITH HOOK} (\gl{ɱ}, \acro{IPA} Extensions block).

 In Junicode the recommended input is {\Ji{m\&\_\_p;\&\_\_d;}}; it
 now renders {\gl{m\&\_\_p;\&\_\_d;}}, i.e., the \acro{MUFI} (Medieval
 Font Unicode Initiative\footnote{\tbsurl{mufi.info}}) Private Use
 Area character \mcode{F223}\footnote{For referencing \acro{MUFI} codepoints
   I advocate the use of the \acro{M+} prefix.} \uname{LATIN SMALL LETTER M
   WITH RIGHT DESCENDER}. This may change in the future.

% can
%  be used, the glyph   {\gl{m\&\_\_d;\&\_\_c;}} can be accessed as {\Ji{m\&\_\_d;\&\_\_c;}}
 
\subsection{\textit{grossum n}}
 \label{sec:grossum-n}

 Similar to \textit{grossum m}, this is the letter \textit{n} as
 written at the end of words.  As discussed in
 \cite[pp.~48--49]{bień22:_parkos}, the intended shape of the letter is not
 clear; see also Fig.~\ref{fig:ParkoszN}.
 
