\section{Special use letters}
 \label{sec:special-use-letters}


 To this category belong the letters with the standard shape, but with
 a non-standard (from the contemporary point of view) phoneme assigned
 to them by Parkosz. They are: \textit{f molle}, \textit{g per se},
 \textit{l durum}, \textit{m molle}, \textit{n molle}.

 All three editions used for these just the standard letters, which
 is quite confusing for present-day readers, even if they are
 scholars. Therefore the decision was made to transliterate them as,
 respectively:
 \begin{itemize}\raggedright
 \item \ucode{1E1F} \uname{LATIN SMALL LETTER F WITH DOT ABOVE} (\gl{ḟ}),
 \item \ucode{0121} \uname{LATIN SMALL LETTER G WITH DOT ABOVE} (\gl{ġ}),
 \item \ucode{1E37} \uname{LATIN SMALL LETTER L WITH DOT BELOW} (\gl{ḷ}),
 \item \ucode{1E43} \uname{LATIN SMALL LETTER M WITH DOT BELOW} (\gl{ṃ}),
 \item \ucode{1E47} \uname{LATIN SMALL LETTER N WITH DOT BELOW} (\gl{ṇ}),
 \end{itemize}

 This part of my proposal can be considered an unnecessary
 complication, so should be treated as optional. Nevertheless in
 Junicode the characters can be entered as, respectively:
 {\Ji{f\&\_\_p;\&\_\_d;}} ({\gl{f\&\_\_p;\&\_\_d;}}\/),
 {\Ji{g\&\_\_p;\&\_\_d;}} ({\gl{g\&\_\_p;\&\_\_d;}}),
 {\Ji{l\&\_\_p;\&\_\_b;}} ({\gl{l\&\_\_p;\&\_\_b;}}),
 {\Ji{m\&\_\_p;\&\_\_b;}} ({\gl{m\&\_\_p;\&\_\_b;}}) and
 {\Ji{n\&\_\_p;\&\_\_b;}} ({\gl{n\&\_\_p;\&\_\_b;}}).

 If used in colored text, it would be desirable to render the dot in a
 different color to make clear this is an artificial addition (an idea
 of Jakub Wilk formulated long ago in a different context). I am aware
 that because of technical difficulties this is at present rather
 a dream.
 

\section{Regular letters}
 \label{sec:regular-letters}

 There is no typographical problem with the letters listed below. We
 give their names using original early Latin spelling (\textit{breue}
 meaning \textit{breve}, i.e., `short').

 They are:
  \gl{a} (\textit{breue}),
 \gl{c}, \gl{d} (\textit{per se}), \gl{e} (\textit{breue}),
\gl{i} (\textit{breue}),
\gl{ÿ}, 
\gl{k},
 \gl{o} (\textit{breue}),
\gl{q} (\textit{per se}),
\gl{r} and \gl{R} (\textit{per
   se}, see also
 section~\ref{sec:majuscules}), \gl{ſ} and \gl{s},
\gl{t},
\gl{u} (\textit{breue}),
\gl{v}, \gl{w}
and \gl{x}.


As for an unnamed variant of the letter \gl{c}, it is not obvious how
to interpret it. I assumed this is \ucode{00E7} \uname{LATIN SMALL
  LETTER C WITH CEDILLA} (\gl{ç}, Latin-1 Supplement block) and
transcribed as such. However in Junicode there is a special glyph for
it, namely {\gl{c\&\_\_p;\&\_\_h;}} input as {\Ji{c\&\_\_p;\&\_\_h;}}.

In Junicode \textit{long s} \gl{s\&\_\_l;\&\_\_o;} can be input as
{\Ji{s\&\_\_l;\&\_\_o;}}.
\section{Letters not listed in the alphabet summary}
 \label{sec:letters-not-listed}
 
 Most old Polish texts for the nasal vowel use \ucode{A7C1}
 \uname{LATIN SMALL LETTER OLD POLISH O} (\sgl{ꟁ}) 
 introduced to Unicode in version 14.0
 \cite{buncic:_propos_old_polis_o_iso}.  However in Parkosz's treatise
 the vowel has the shape of \ucode{00F8} \uname{LATIN SMALL LETTER O
   WITH STROKE} \gl{ø}, cf.~the second and the third stroked
 letter in Fig.~\ref{fig:nosowe}, so it was used in the
 transliteration. However in Junicode it can be input as
 {\Ji{ꟁ\&\_\_p;\&\_\_s;}} which makes its meaning clear.

 The manuscript contains a single occurrence of \ucode{2C65}
 \uname{LATIN SMALL LETTER A WITH STROKE} (\sgl{ⱥ}), cf.~the first stroked
 letter in Fig.~\ref{fig:nosowe}, which could be a scribal mistake.
 Nevertheless it was transcribed just as \gl{ⱥ}. 

 \begin{figure}
   \centering
 \includegraphics[width=\hsize]{img/16-7-2trimmed}
   \caption{Nasal vowels in the manuscript}
   \label{fig:nosowe}
 \end{figure}

 Letter \gl{z} was omitted in the alphabet, probably by mistake; in
 the transliteration it was used without change, which is a
 simplification, as it looks more like \gl{ʒ} \ucode{0292}
 \uname{LATIN SMALL LETTER EZH}.

 The letter \gl{h} was also omitted probably by mistake.

 \section{Multigraphs}
 \label{sec:multigraphs}

 Some multigraphs in the manuscript are written as ligatures, but
 there is no need to represent them as such in the transliteration. On
 the other hand it would be desirable if the font rendered them as
 ligatures.

 As it was mentioned earlier, some multigraphs consist of doubled vowels:
 \textit{longum} \textit{aa},
  \textit{longum} \textit{ee},
 \textit{longum}  \textit{oo},
 \textit{longum}  \textit{uu}.

 There is an open question whether the text would be more readable if
\textit{longum} \textit{aa} was rendered as \ucode{A733} \uname{LATIN SMALL
   LETTER AA} ({\sgl{ꜳ}}, Latin Ex\-\mbox{tended-D}) and \textit{longum} \textit{oo}
 as \ucode{A74F} \uname{LATIN SMALL LETTER OO} ({\sgl{ꝏ}}, also
 Latin Extended-D). For \textit{longum} \textit{ee} and \textit{uu}
the  ligatures would have to be designed. The character \mcode{E8C7}
 \uname{LATIN SMALL LIGATURE UU} (\sgl{}) would be rather
 misleading.

 The other multigraphs are: \sgli{ch} (taken over from Latin), \sgli{cz}, \textit{molle}
 \sgli{dz}, \sgli{ſſz}, \sgli{ſch} and
 \sgli{ſz}, and \sgli{zz}.

 \section{Majuscules}
 \label{sec:majuscules}

 Some of the examples are proper names, so they usually (not always)
 start with a majuscule  (cf.\ the index in
\cite{kucała20:_trakt_jakub_parkos}).

 The main Polish example is a verse, and the first
 words of some lines also start with a majuscule.

 \begin{figure*}[ht]\centering
   \includegraphics[width=\hsize]{img/parkosz15l24}
   \caption{The manuscript p.~15 l.~24: \Junicode {Ɓoç} {ʋṇye{ɱ}{}}
     {kaſzde} {ſḷoʋko} {thoɓe} (transliteration)}
   \label{fig:Bmolle}
 \end{figure*}


 In consequence the transcription contained the following
 majuscules: \gl{A},
  \gl{Ɓ} (\textit{B molle}, cf.\ Fig.~\ref{fig:Bmolle}),
 \gl{C},
 \gl{Ġ} (\textit{G per se}),
 \gl{I},
 \gl{K},
 \gl{N},
 \Sgl{Ᵽ} (\textit{P grossum}),
 {\gl{Ƥ}} (\textit{P molle}),
 \gl{Q},
 \gl{R},
 \gl{S},
 \gl{V},
 \gl{T},
 \gl{Z}.

 In Junicode we have now {\gl{P\&\_\_p;\&\_\_s;}} input as
 {\Ji{P\&\_\_p;\&\_\_s;}} and {\gl{P\&\_\_p;\&\_\_r;}} input
 as {\Ji{P\&\_\_p;\&\_\_r;}};
 \gl{G\&\_\_p;\&\_\_d;} can be input as {\Ji{G\&\_\_p;\&\_\_d;}}.

 
 It is perhaps worth noting that the upper case of \textit{g per se}
 is \gl{I}.

 

 \section{Concluding remarks}
 \label{sec:concluding-remarks}

 Adding Parkosz's letter to Junicode is in my opinion a large step
 forward in improving the editorial quality of publications concerning
 the treatise. Elsewhere I intend to present the difficulties caused
 by the lack of an appropriate font, including a misrepresentation of
 Parkosz's views.
 
 It would be fun to have also a font simulating original handwriting,
 but the text would be unreadable for people without at least some
 knowledge of paleography; see, for example, the letters \textit{d} and
 \textit{x} shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:Pilas2}.

